author: Associated Press in Cairo
title: Bodies of 74 migrants wash ashore in Libya
text:
Bodies of 74 migrants wash ashore in Libya 
Red Crescent says the circumstances surrounding the drowning in western city of Zawiya are not yet clear The Red Crescent said the bodies washed ashore on Tuesday morning. Photograph: Guardian Graphics for the Guardian View more sharing options Tuesday 21 February 2017 09.49 GMT Last modified on Tuesday 21 February 2017 09.54 GMT 
The bodies of 74 migrants and refugees have washed ashore in the western Libyan city of Zawiya on the Mediterranean coast, Libya’s Red Crescent has said. 
Mohammed al-Misrati, the aid organisation’s spokesman, said the bodies had washed ashore on Tuesday morning. 
Misrati said the circumstances surrounding the drowning were not yet clear. The agency posted photographs on its Twitter account of dozens of bodies in white and black body bags, lined up along the shore. 
Misrati said local authorities would take the bodies to a cemetery allocated for unidentified persons in Tripoli. 
Migrant deaths have risen to record levels along the Libya-Italy smuggling route across the Mediterranean Sea. 
More details soon …
